Rating: 4
Probably the most eye-rolling good thing I've ever made from this site. I've made this a few times now, and here are my lessons learned: (1) varying the dairy (proportions of cream and milk) is scarcely noticeable as long as the total amount is respected; (2) because of the high sugar content, the mixture needs to be chilled to ice- cold before adding to a home ice-cream maker or it won't get thick; (3) yes, you do have to strain the custard; and (4) *this is key*: making caramel requires good light and nerves of steel. Make sure you have your cream right next to the pot and ready to pour. In the 30 seconds it takes to open a cream carton your caramel can go from perfect to burnt - but to get the best flavour it needs to be almost too dark. Salt will counteract the emerging bitterness of a darker caramel. (Any reviewers who found this bland used a too-light caramel.)

