The ice cream is spectacular. Let's just start with that. After reading many of the reviews I made a couple of decisions that changed the process a bit. 1) Temper the eggs to cut down on the "scrambled' effect in the custard. 2) Add more milk (2%) to cut the richness. I also found that the suggestions to warm the cream were critical to decreasing the amount of caramel that seized. A warning: if you think the stirring process will be quick you are wrong. It took me about 40 minutes to stir the hardened caramel back into the warm cream - I kept the burner on very low during the process to aid the melting. I'd give this a four but it was very involved - much more than I thought. I would have expected it to take 30 minutes to make the custard and caramel but I ended up spending more like an hour and 15 minutes from start to chill. Leave the mixture in the fridge for a few hours (at least four) before you even try to freeze. It also firms up nicely if you give it an overnight before you pair it with warm brownies for desert. We used the layered brownies with white-chocolate caramel recipe from this site.

