Oh My Goodness. I have made a lot of ice cream and gelato in my time, but this is one of the best. I had no problems with the caramel or the custard. I did double the sea salt to 1 teaspoon based on others' reviews. Plan to serve with brownies but really it needs no accompaniment. Could also imagine with an apple dessert as others have suggested or with an espresso poured over.

Rating: 4
It's my first time making ice cream, but what success! This was AMAZING. Silky, deeply caramel, rich and decadent. I had some trouble with the caramel but lots of patient stirring helped (I crushed up the remaining chunks of sugar and added it as a crunchy topping). We could not wait for the icecream to firm up and had some in a rather liquid pudding texture! (Like flan, said my partner!) The recipe makes an icecream that is a little too sweet for my preference, so next time I'll use a tad more salt to cut thru the sweetness and use about half the caramel; the extra caramel can serve as a topping for those with a sweeter tooth. Fantastic recipe!

Rating: 0
Wow. Like the others, I can't get over the texture of this ice cream. Very much like gelato- so velvety smooth. Per some other suggestions, I heated the cream before pouring it into the carmel. I'm not sure it helped, because it took a loooong time to melt the carmel back down into liquid after it initially seized up. That said, it did eventually melt and I did not need to use a sieve. I did pick out one little chunk that didn't melt down. I used a low heat on the custard until I got impatient and then turned it up to high, whisking the whole time. It never did get to 175 degrees on the thermometer, but coated the spoon. It got a little bit "textured"- not quite like scrambled eggs- but I didn't bother to strain it. Cooled the custard and the carmel in ice baths, combined them afterwards, chilled a little more, and into the ice cream canister they went. In 30 minutes it was done. Even without the straining through a sieve, the texture is amazing. I will add about 1/4- 1/2 more salt next time. Since I couldn't find "flaky" sea salt ANYWHERE in my little town, I used regular fine sea salt and ground it finer using a morter and pestle. PERFECTION. I'm serving it tomorrow with an apple crumble. Ooohh. :)

Rating: 4
There were a couple times I thought I was in trouble making this. First, it initially seemed I had made rock candy instead of caramel. If you keep melting it, though, it will eventually smooth out fine. Secondly, I cooked the custard a little too much and had to discard some egg. Neither problem had any effect on the ice cream as far as I can tell. This is a serious dessert. I wouldn't hesitate to call it the most tempting I've ever made. It calls you back. It demands.

Rating: 4
Just as good as my favorite burnt caramel ice cream from Toscanini's (Cambridge, MA)! I am amazed that I can make this at home. I was worried about making the caramel, but it turned out that the custard was the part I messed up -- I wasn't paying attention while it was heating and didn't stir. It basically turned into pudding. But after forcing it through a sieve and discarding some of the solids, it was fine. I substituted 2% milk, which I had on hand, for all the whole milk and 1/4 cup of the cream. It still tasted rich and creamy, so I would do this again to cut down on some of the fat.

